</p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have deliberately chosen to work with schools in some of the most deprived areas of the country.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Almost a third (30%) of our students are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eligible for Free School Meals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">whilst nearly a quarter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">%) of students speak English as a Fore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ign Language and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">22% have Special Educational Needs.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Breaking the link between deprivation and low educational attainment is one of our central aims</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is important to make some distinctions in talking about the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">impact of becoming an academy.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">do not believe that changing the legal status of a school necessarily has any impact on achievement, progress or the quality of education.  However, the process of becoming an academy can have a significant impact if it i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nvolves </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an appropriate mixture of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">putting in place strong governance and outstanding leadership, re-thinking the nature of the school and its curriculum to serve pupils better, implementing strong systems to support teaching, track pupils and improve behav</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iour and investing in the professional development of staff.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If these things are done well, and with a focus on improving the attainment of the least advantage, the impact can be significant.  Where appropriate support is provided from other schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">withi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n a group </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or a wider network, backed by effective challenge and accountability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, this impact can be enhanced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Overall, our view is that these core factors are more important than the legal flexibilities of academy status.  The general sense that school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">leaders have of being able to determine their own destiny is, however, important.  There is probably nothing in the legal structure of the National Curriculum which would prevent, for example, the use of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> different forms of tuition for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">those joining halfway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through the academic year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> those whose literacy and numeracy is behind </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">expectation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, heads in our schools have confidence to trial and adopt approaches without fear of constraint.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We continue to focus our efforts on schools in challenging cir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cumstances.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The vast majority of schools that have joined us have done so from a position of under-performance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, in which both advantaged and disadvantaged had lagged well behind national averages.  The key to improvement has in the end been human – outsta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nding teaching and leadership.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Being an academy is not a pre-requisite for this but it is true that none of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">state </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">schools that joined us </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as sponsored </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academies had succeeded </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">before doing so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While not every academy is part of a larger group of networ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">k, there are benefits of being so.  In particular, access to expertise in relation to data and educational improvement, high quality expertise in relation to particular educational issues, professional development and support in business management, financ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e, HR and IT have significant benefits.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Likewise, the ability to benchmark against a group of schools facing some similar issues has been valuable, as has the creation of opportunities to share ideas and practice within a safe environment of colleagues wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o are working to achieve the same ends within a single organisation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Overall, these factors explain the data on improvement in academies.  These suggest strongly that in sponsored academies of the sort we run, academy conversion has had a positive impact </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on attainment and progress compared to similar schools which are not sponsored academies.  The effect is greatest in schools which are part of larger groups.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Taking our schools overall, there has been significant narrowing of the gap between most and leas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t disadvantaged in relation to attainment and progress.  Pupils who were lower attaining on entry have benefitted particularly.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0p