t">We enjoy st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rong and positive relationships </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with the DfE and the EFA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they deserve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a great deal of credit for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">number of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have been establis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">over the past three years.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  We also wish to work constructively with predecessor schools, local communities and local authorities and in general the processes allow us to do this.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">welcome the end of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">OSC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“beauty parades” that occurred in the first </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the Coalition which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> were hugely costly in terms of resource for sponsors.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  More generally, the DfE is working to ensure that governors who have been part of the problem of a school’s decline are not the decision-makers as to who should be the sponsor.  This is not always suc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cessful, but is improving.  The powers that the Department is using in relation to sponsored academies were in fact designed for the converter process, and this is sometimes a problem.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> serious obstacle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> straightforward transition to academy status</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s where the predecessor school is part of a PFI. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Resolving the issues associated with this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is exceptionally problematic practically and in principle.  Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e extent and potential future variation in PFI payments that the academy will need to make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and falls o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sponsor to underwrite</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which is seriously problematic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe this is a problem faced by several sponsors. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To date</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it is has delayed conversion on two </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academy projects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> full</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> year.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We have incurred extensive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and unrecoverable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">costs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on both projects.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Free School application process works well for an established sponsor with a clear track record.  Our new schools are being established in areas with significant demand for new places and with strong local support; they draw on our e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">xperience of providing excellent education in areas of substantial challenge and connect to other schools we run in the area. The biggest difficulty for us is in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> securing buildings in which to house the schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, where we are typically dependent on local au</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">thorities and the EFA in areas where there is not significant spare land</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Such uncertainty not only risks the future </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of these projects but delays lead to significant costs for us as sponsor as well as reputational harm. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">More importantly, it can mean</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that a year group of pupils will be unable to take up places at a Free School </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there is demand for.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The role of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting faili</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ng</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> academies and how this role will work as the Programme expands</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The functi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ons and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> support for schools at this level</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As we move </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3,500 academies, the DfE is increasingly stretched in intervening in and supporting failing academies.  As we move</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to 20,000 academies across the country, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it will be unrealistic to expect the Department to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">carry out these roles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">By its very nature, a central Department cannot have detailed local knowledge about every part of the country.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Even more unrealistic would be expecting the DfE to have the ability to tackle coasting schools or spot poor admi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ssions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or exclusions practice.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It seems to us therefore, that it is inevitable that the challenge and support role will need to be devolved to another body.  The central question is whether this should be the local authority or another intermediate body.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">think that the local authority should have a clear role in relation to sufficiency (enough school places in the right place); access (ensuring that pupils can get to school and have a fair chance of getting into favoured schools); and the vulnerable (ensur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing that those who need additional support get it).  No other body is better set up to carry out these functions.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The reality is that local education authorities and their predecessors were not established to provide school improvement – this role was add</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed later.  It is therefore unsurprising that the quality of authorities’ school improvement work has varied markedly across the country.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Other approaches (especially school-to-school support) appear to be more consistently effective.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, we would</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> argue that school improvement should not be a core local authority function.  Local authorities can reasonably have a role in brokering support from a variety of sources, but should not necessarily be expected to provide their own in-house service.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould not prevent effective school improvement functions from continuing as traded services.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Even more contentious is a potential local authority challenge or accountability role with academies.  We understand that where a local authority is also a signi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ficant provider of schools, it may be seen by some to have a conflict of interest if it is also part of the accountability system.  However, we do not instinctively favour the creation of another tier of government to carry out this function at the regiona</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l level.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, we would argue that where a local authority is no longer a provider of (say) secondary schools, it can reasonably be given a role in challenging and holding to account providers of schools.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We can foresee a system where funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agreements continue to be held by central government but take a different form – something like renewable licences – and are monitored locally against agreed performance targets.  Agreements need to be long enough (e.g. at least five years) to allow contin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uity but their renewal would be automatic only if the agreed aims are achieved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (using the lessons from, for example, the Credo Charter School Study (2013)).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> If they are not, and a provider cannot achieve improvement in a defined period of time, then the pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ovider would be replaced, through an open competition run and decided locally but leading to a funding agreement with national government.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While this may be contentious, it gives teeth to the local authority’s role as a champion of pupils and parents and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensures that a school which is not giving a good service can be challenged locally by those who know it best.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Secretary of State </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should continue to hold</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sponsors to account for their overall performance.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfE must retain the right to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">prevent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> spons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ors </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from growing, to challenge their use of public money</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and, where necessary, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">remov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Master </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Funding Agreement.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since academy groups differ so much from one another (e.g. some provide significant finance, HR and IT support, some focus on data and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> professional development), we are not clear what is meant by ‘inspection of academy chains’.  We are not clear how much value Ofsted could add </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> looking at how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> support is provided, for example. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ofsted already reports on the performance of sponsors i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n supporting schools as part of its inspection of governance in sponsored academies.  We think that how well they support schools is a key success measure for academy groups, and is the key issue about such groups on which Ofsted is qualified to comment.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ofsted could already report on this through analysing its inspection data from inspections of sponsored academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e are unclear how much value would be added by ‘inspecting chains’ over and above simple publication of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">data on sponsor performance which O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fsted already holds.  We would welcome this latter approach.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">arrangements</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At the outset, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academy chains were highly centralised levers for controlling change; successful in dealing with the first generation of academies which needed transformational intervention. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, while this approach is appropriate in turning around a failing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">institution, it is insufficient to create sustainable excellence.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The long-t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erm success of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> academies will come from their ability to thrive locally with the support of cost-effective </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">central </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from a g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">roup. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">group will continue to have high exp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ectations, strong performance management and appropriate systems.  However, it will equally importantly focus on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sharing of best practice, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">providing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> training and CPD for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> staff and investing i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">educational and capital </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">projects.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Over the past 18 months, we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have taken a series of steps to increase local autonomy and accountability for our academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, within a clearly agreed framework</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Five year plans have been agreed between the centre and schools, setting out a shared strategic direction.  Within that, local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> governing bodies have responsibilities to ensure proper implementation of that plan in the light of changing local circumstances and to challenge heads and senior teams on performance and improvement.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While Ofsted has sometimes struggled to understand go</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vernance and accountability in multi-academy trusts, this model ensures that schools have very clear and sharp accountabilities.  Performance management of heads, led from the centre, together with local challenge and support make a strong combination.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erall, this means that accountability of schools is sharp.  Accountability of sponsors is sharp too.  At each school inspection, the contribution of the sponsor to governance is assessed.  School results are published and widely scrutinised.  The Departmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t for Education holds sponsors sharply to account – organising visits by advisers and reviews as well as challenging sponsors in meetings.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have set out above some ways in which this could be sharpened further.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The appropriateness of academy status for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> primary schools and what special factors apply; and what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academies p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rogramme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for primary schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is less established than its secondary equivalent, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and there is a less clear evidence base</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iven the size and budgets of individual primary schools, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are not convinced that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> stand-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">alone primary academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will be sustainable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">makes more sense for pri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mary academies to join a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">federation, a National Teaching School alliance or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> wider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">roup. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A single primary school is vulnerable to leadership or governance change.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As part of a group, there is considerable potential for economies and efficiencies throu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gh shared purchasing, support and access to partnered resource that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">smaller </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stand-alone academies cannot deliver on their own.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is therefore a key role for partnership working and peer-to-peer support which has the potential to grow.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a group we ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ve been keen to build clusters of primary schools so that, by working together, they can offer more for less; both in terms of education and administrative support.  Likewise, we have looked </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">add </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">primary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">schools in areas where we have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">secondary strength </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">so that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> can share costs and build a stronger educational relationship that prepares primary pupils for secondary education.  In our experience, this is proving extremely effective. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that there is more that Government should be doing to poin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t converter academies towards academy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">groups</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Closure should always remain an option for a failing school whether</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it is an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> academy or local authority run. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Other than joining a group, a hard federation which secures the long term commitment of an excellent Executive Headteacher is a strong approach. This may provide a longer term solution than the use of an NLE which can be effective, but who ultimately has l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">imited power and accountability and whose length of involvement with the school may be limited.  However, there are clearly good examples of NLE or Teaching School Alliance leadership of improvement.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sometimes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">taken the decision to begin working w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ith failing schools before they formally join our Group so that no time is lost in beginning to address serious weakness.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Because of our size and scope we are able to afford to do this. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Often failing primary schools have significant budgetary deficits an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d are therefore unable to afford to pay for additional support. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If they are ultimately joining us, then we understand the need for us to invest in them in advance (often with some financial support from the DfE). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Any new model, therefore, should be able </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to encourage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">joining a group or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">federation and external support in a way that is cost-neutral to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">parties.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>